                     <interp inst="t17530607-19-off88" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17530607-19-off88" type="offenceSubcategory" value="pocketpicking"></interp>
               stealing one silk handkerchief, val. 1 s. 6 d. the property of a person unknown, privately from his person
            </rs>, <rs id="t17530607-19-cd89" type="crimeDate">June 1</rs>
                  <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t17530607-19-off88 t17530607-19-cd89"></join>. ++</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17530607-19-person171">
                  William 
                  Lee 
               <interp inst="t17530607-19-person171" type="surname" value="Lee"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17530607-19-person171" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17530607-19-person171" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a journeyman-baker and live in Southwark, on Friday was se'ennight I had occasion to go to the <placeName id="t17530607-19-crimeloc90">Exchange</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17530607-19-crimeloc90" type="placeName" value="Exchange"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17530607-19-crimeloc90" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17530607-19-off88 t17530607-19-crimeloc90"></join>, and as I was sitting on a bench there about two o'clock, a gentleman had one corner of his handkerchief hanging out of his pocket; I saw the prisoner take hold on it and pull it out, and held it under his coat behind him. I secured the prisoner, and carried him before my lord-mayor, where he was searched and this handkerchief taken out of his pocket. Produced in court. It is the very same I saw him take out of the gentleman's pocket.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17530607-19-person172">
